atrix elements of the translation operator are:\n\n\u27e8x D(a) x\u2032\u27e9\n\n=\n\n\u03b4((x \u2212x\u2032) \u2212a)\n\n(5.27)\n\nFor an infinitesimal translation we write:\n\n\u27e8x (\u02c61 \u2212i\u03b4a\u02c6p) x\u2032\u27e9\n\n=\n\n\u03b4(x \u2212x\u2032) \u2212\u03b4a\u03b4\u2032(x \u2212x\u2032)\n\n(5.28)\n\nHence we deduce:\n\n\u27e8x \u02c6p x\u2032\u27e9\n\n=\n\n\u2212i\u03b4\u2032(x \u2212x\u2032)\n\n(5.29)\n\n24\n\nWe notice that the delta function is symmetric, so its derivative is anti-symmetric.\n\nIn analogy to multiplying a\n\nmatrix with a column vector we write: \u02c6A \u03a8\u27e97\u2192P\n\nj Aij\u03a8j. Let us examine how the momentum opertor operates on\n\na \u201dwavefunction\u201d:\n\n\u02c6p \u03a8\u27e9\n\n7\u2192\n\nX\n\nx\u2032\n\n\u02c6pxx\u2032\u03a8x\u2032 =\n\nZ\n\n\u27e8x \u02c6p", "embedding": [-0.02270942, -0.02213123, 0.05656782, -0.014515602, 0.027265783, -0.00056171895, -0.023339547, -0.0019057106, -0.05791559, 0.063944414, 0.03980491, 0.014818159, -0.01221909, -0.01895502, -0.001986741, 0.027460808, -0.0098596, -0.024937099, -0.036321316, 0.013334763, 0.043048523, -0.0005075489, -0.08814354, -0.025200123, 0.0042535574, 0.026398918, 0.045932677, 0.013864725, 0.05276133, 0.050092615, 0.032327954, -0.004490723, 0.065212585, -0.03842143, -0.00039813184, 0.010018071, 0.0039890097, -0.022706138, 0.0043937787, -0.03542067, 0.027346285, 0.018094929, 0.017098723, 0.0073312935, -0.06359532, -0.04132951, -0.02521655, 0.0049175606, -0.038330838, -0.040425092, -0.0043547945, -0.015985651, 0.03937224, -0.04905621, -0.024159588, 0.011625322, 0.021702973, 0.00070136675, -0.0027237579, 0.047355413, 0.0047653373, -0.00554292, -0.0195987, -0.036640763, 0.007295314, -0.017697327, -0.011222153, 0.022647547, 0.01772164, -0.069145314, 0.010760237, 0.0035415788, -0.032449085, -0.0058851778, -0.037805337, 0.046227388, -0.032002833, -0.0067728986, -0.06230186, 0.008888615, 0.016108193, -0.027728919, 0.00589925, 0.002559763, -0.017570632, -0.015584